"Pieris rapae","2017-05-16 13:28:00 -0700","The butterfly Pieris rapae, or most commonly known as the cabbage white, is very common in Europe and North American and also Wallowa County. They are also found in Asia and almost any man made area. Pieris rapae belongs to the Animalia kingdom because it is multicellular and is a heterotroph that relies on other organisms for food. It is part of the phylum Arthropoda because it is invertebrate with a segmented body, joined legs, and contains an exoskeleton. The class that Pieris rapae is placed in is Insecta. This class has three main body parts, six legs, and two antennae. The rapae species is in the order Lepidoptera because it means to have scales and wings, just like moths and butterflies. This butterfly is a member of the Pieris family and is most commonly known as the Cabbage White. 
All butterflies go through a morphological stage through metamorphosis. The insect first starts as an egg and moults and turns into a pupa through time. After rising from the pupa stage, the organism grows and becomes and adult butterfly. Pieris rapae begin as yellow egg with 12 longitudinal ridges that are places singularly on their host plant. As young caterpillars, they are bluish-green with tiny black pints. They also have a black ring around the spiracles, a lateral row of yellow dashes, and a yellow middorsal line. The pupa of Pieris rapae are brown, gray, and yellowish to match the background of their surroundings. It has a large head cone, with a vertical abdomen and flared sub dorsal ridge. The pupa begin to grow into adults in the chrysalis and will later emerge as adult butterflies. 
Pieris rapae can be easily identified from its other family members. Many other members of the Pieris family consist of marbling on the underside of the hindwing. In comparison, Cabbage Whites do not have those certain characteristics, but do have some of their very own. They are most commonly known for their bright white or yellow color and their famous dots on their wings. Females have two black dots on their lower forewings with one dot on their upper hindwing, while males only have one dot on each wing. The Cabbage White is the only species of its family that has both unmarked hindwing undersides and at least one black spot on the forewing upper side and the leading edge of the hindwing upper side. They’re wingspan usually ranges from 30 to 50 mm long and this specimen had a wingspan of 40mm. 
Pieris rapae are usually adults from the months of March to October and are most commonly seen within that time. Butterflies reproduce sexually. When a male spots a female, the butterfly zig zags and flies around her until she lands. The male flutters, catches her closed forewings with his legs, and spreads his wings. He usually flies a short distance with her beneath him. The male passes a small pack of sperm to the female.  Each egg gets fertilized while the sperm passes through the egg laying tube. Female butterflies will lay their eggs singularly on their host plants using the oils from mustard plants. 
My specimen was found near the hostplants that they live on. It was found in a residential backyard, fluttering around the garden bed. The bed was located in Enterprise, Oregon. The Cabbage White was found on a sunny day when the skies were blue. There were also other species in my back yard surrounding the butterfly I collected. There were dandelions, grass, cabbages, and raspberry plants. It was one of the most common areas Cabbage Whites are found along with man made areas, in town, and valley ranges. The GPS coordinates were 45o25’19”N, 117o16’18”W on the East aspect. This specimen has adapted to its surroundings through time. It is a male with more of a bright white color which allowed it to blend in with its surroundings. He did not stand out intensively and this trait would allow him to hide from predators. The colors of Cabbage Whites are crucial in order to blend in with their habitat.

"Pieris rapae","2016-10-19 05:53:00 -1000","Scientific and Common Name
Scientific name: Pieris rapae Common Name: Cabbage White Butterfly.
Habitat and Geographic range 
Pieris rapae is an invasive species originating from Europe. Pieris rapae was introduce in Quebec city, New York City, Chicago, Florida, Charleston and Indiana and has since spread through North America. After the initial invasion of P.rapae in Quebec city the species begun to spread through west Quebec and into Ontario at a rate of 42.6 +3.0 kilometers per year, more information including geographical diagrams and statistical evidence of the dispersion of P.rapae can be found in Spread of invading organisms (Andow, Kareiva, Levin, & Okubo, 1990). These species can still be found throughout Europe and Australia (Jones, 1987). The invading species have adapted to live in a variety of habitats including grasslands, Tallgrass, foothills of Grasslands and Riparian, Montane woodlands and Plains Riparian (Robinson, Armstead, & Deane Bowers, 2012). In a study done by Robinson et al confirmed that P.rapae was more commonly found in Plains Riparian site where P.rapae composed of 89% of the butterfly population recorded in their study (Robinson, Armstead, & Deane Bowers, 2012). 
Size/Weight and Lifespan
The size of the P.rapae above is roughly 60 mm in length and 50mm in width with a tear in the top left wing. The weight of the P.rapae above, although not officially weighed, would approximately weigh between 2-3 grams. The lifespan of P.rapae begins when the female lays her eggs on a host plant. After the eggs hatch, the caterpillars remain on the host plant for 10-20 days until it reaches metamorphosis. Once P.rapae has transformed into its final stage of life it is ready to mate. The female of this species can live to three weeks after laying her eggs (Gilbert,1984).. In the study conducted by N. Gilbert, there is evidence that larger P.rapae survive better at every stage of life and can lay more eggs than smaller P.rapae (Gilbert, 1984). P.rapae can live up to five generations in a year (Jones,1987).
Diet 
Juvenile P. rapae consume nutrients that are in the host plant that the parent P.rapae has chosen for them. These host plants are typically a wide selection of wild and domesticated species of the Brassica genus or the mustard genus (Kingsolver, 2000). Adult P.rapae consume protein rich pollen from nearby angiosperms (Wiklund, Karlsson,& Leimar, 2001). 
Reproduction & Communication 
Reproduction in the P.rapae species occurs during the autumn months of the year, when the female is able to absorb certain UV rays between 380-400 mu and reflect them in her wings, communicating to the males that the female is ready to mate (Obara,1970). In an experiment by Obara they discovered that male P.rapae are able to easily differentiate between males and female. They set up fake male and female dummies and recorded the number of times the dummy was visited. The female dummy was visited 106 by males and the male dummy was virtually not visited at all (Obara,1970). When the female signals that she is ready to copulate, she is in a resting position on a plant leaf or the ground. There is no visible or apparent forms of courtship (Obara,1970). If the female has already mated or is refusing to mate with the male, she will open her wings and arch her abdomen so that it is perpendicular to the ground (Obara,1970). Once the female is impregnated she will find a suitable host plant and lay her eggs, where they will hatch and remain on the host plant until the juveniles reach metamorphosis (Kingsolver, 2000). 
Predators 
P.rapae have numerous natural predators notably insect parasitoids, social wasps (Jones,1987), and different species of birds, including garden warblers, tits and house sparrows (Baker, 1970). In the experiment conducted by Robin Baker, bird predation on P.rapae was recorded. They discovered that house sparrows and tits were the main predators of P.rapae (Baker,1970). In another study conducted in Australia, researchers concluded that ant predation has a significant impact on the mortality of P.rapae, However ant predation is effected by season and location, and P.rapae can have four to five generations per year, allowing at least one generation of P.rapae to be ant predation free (Jones,1987). The study also demonstrates evidence that parasitized P.rapae by braconid wasps were more heavily preyed upon than non-parasitized P.rapae (Jones,1987).
Conservation Status 
The P.rapae being able to produce four to five generation per year, its successfully invasion of  North America, and its ability to continually adapt to ecological niches, has increased its presence throughout the world, and is safe from any threat to the species’ survival (Kingsolver, 2000). 
Fun Fact
Did you know that P.rapae gets its common name Cabbage White Butterfly from the P.rapae using various domesticated species of cabbages as host plants when laying their eggs? As P.rapae do not leave their host plant, most cabbages become infested with P.rapae and they are considered to be an agricultural nuisance (Kingsolver, 2000).

The area was heavily vegetated with small, close to the ground plants. There were few flowers, but not many. "Pieris rapae","2016-03-03 13:35:00 +1300","Today the butterflies were only landing and interacting with the Convolulus cneorum. The taller shrub was not landed on once, in comparison to the other observation where the butterflies were predominantly landing on the shrub. The butterflies were landing within the flowers and extending their proboscis into the center of the flower, making the plant a feeding plant. After a visit to an individual bloom, another butterfly was not deterred from this bloom and would also feed from the same bloom. Additionally, butterflies would sometimes compete for/share the same bloom.
Removed from the plant, the butterflies would sometimes hover over other species of plants, including blooms, but not land on them. The butterflies would circle/interact with each other in the air, sometimes make circles around the lawn or fly straight up to the sky at roof height (single story). 
Due to the warmer weather and lack of morning overcast the butterflies were able to just feed and not worry about heating themselves up on the taller shrubs, facing the sun.","Lincoln University Farm Road Flats",-43.645647,172.461652,"","Cabbage White","http://naturewatch.org.nz/observations/2739307","https://static.inaturalist.org/photos/3092828/medium.jpg?1456974638","tesssprawson",2739307,"Cabbage White","Insecta",55626,"false",1,0,"2016-03-03 1:35pm","2016-03-03","2016-03-02 17:35:00 -0700","Wellington",48,"","","false","","",NA,186834,"2016-03-02 20:10:34 -0700","2016-05-17 14:01:15 -0700","research","CC-BY-NC",NA,"false"

"Pieris rapae","2016-03-01 17:30:00 +1300","The exact location is in a fairly suburban area, closely surrounded by farmland. The temperature was 15 degrees Celsius and it was fairly windy (Beaufort 2), with no precipitation. It began as a mild to cool day with overcast, and by late afternoon the sun came out. The observed space is approx. 3 square meters and situated in the corner of two low rise buildings, facing to the west. 

The butterflies interaction toward the plants varied. There were two instances where butterflies landed on the flowering shrub, Convolvulus cneorum, The butterflies were observed sticking their proboscis into numerous flowers. Also, judging by the amount of honeybees present on the Convolvulus cneorum, it can be assumed that this plant is mainly used for feeding on nectar. However, the taller bush (species unknown) had no blooms and the butterflies seemed more attracted to this location. The bush was observed to be attractive as a resting spot. The butterflies would not extend their proboscis when they landed. The butterflies were also landing, and then opening their wings to the west (the setting sun), so as to absorb the warmth of the sun on the previously cool day perhaps. 

The butterflies were hovering around the bush and flying up to the height of the roof and then back down to the bush. There were no instances of the butterflies landing anywhere but on the plants.

The butterflies rarely appeared individually, but as pairs. There was one pair that interacted and danced around each other.

"Pieris rapae","2016-02-28 11:25:00 +1300","Many of the cabbage white butterflies' favourite plant species on the 27th feb, for example basil, were today in complete shade. This is due to the suns movement throughout the course of the day, as the 27th feb assessment was at 5:10pm and the 28th feb observation was at 11:20am.

By observing the cabbage white butterfly population behaviour, it is clear that they avoid the shade and prefer areas that are in the sun. This is likely justification for why the Basil wasn't utilised today, and instead the population much more readily gathered nectar from dandelions.

The wind was stronger during the 28th observation, noticeably affecting the butterfly behaviour as the amount of time spent resting was reduced (assumedly due to the increased sway in foliage).

The temperature was also a lot lower on the 28th (19 degrees, as opposed to 31 degrees the previous day). This could also justify the reduction in butterfly numbers","555 Collins road, Sprinston, Christchurch",-43.661748,172.420144,"","Cabbage White","http://naturewatch.org.nz/observations/2722115","https://static.inaturalist.org/photos/3071127/medium.jpg?1456614614","james_ranstead",2722115,"Cabbage White","Insecta",55626,"false",1,0,"2016-02-28 11:25 am","2016-02-28","2016-02-27 15:25:00 -0700","Wellington",NA,"","","false","","",NA,183822,"2016-02-27 16:10:10 -0700","2016-05-13 22:45:46 -0700","research","CC-BY-NC",NA,"false"

"Pieris rapae","2016-02-27 17:15:00 +1300","The site of testing had human presence throughout the day, as a person was tending to the garden. Just 5 metres from the site of observation, insecticide granules had been applied to the soil surrounding broccoli seedlings.

Human presence, and the addition of toxins nearby to the site may have altered the species behaviour.

The garden contained species that are required for the larval stage, such as broccoli, and there was cabbage present about a week ago. This is perhaps the reason the local population is so large.

"Pieris rapae","2015-07-11 00:00:00 -0600","Cabbage White (Pieris rapae)

11 July 2015: On Cooper Creek in the Avondale Park area we encountered a Cabbage White (Pieris rapae) perched on green foliage in the shade. This was the first time we've documented this butterfly at Avondale Park and Cooper Creek. According to the Butterflies and Moths of North America Web site, Cabbage White ranges from ""central Canada south through the United States (except Florida Keys, southern Louisiana, and South Texas) to northwest Mexico."" Hence this is a strictly North American butterfly. Because of its flight in North America Cabbage White is an authentic resident of the Western Hemisphere. Avondale Park and Cooper Creek are administered by the City of Denton, Texas.

Source: ""Cabbage White Pieris rapae (Linnaeus, 1758),"" Butterflies and Moths of North America, description, photographs, range map, accessed 11.21.15, http://www.butterfliesandmoths.org/species/Pieris-rapae","Avondale Park, Denton, Texas",33.242657,-97.109358,"Cabbage White (Pieris rapae), Avondale Park, Denton, Texas, butterflies, summer, range, United States, Mexico, vagrant in Canada, North Texas, North America, Western Hemisphere, Butterflies and Moths of North America","Cabbage White","http://www.inaturalist.org/observations/2406673","https://static.inaturalist.org/photos/2685361/medium.jpg?1448164328","aguilita",2406673,"Cabbage White","Insecta",55626,"false",4,0,"2015-07-11","2015-07-11","","Central Time (US & Canada)",307,"","","false","","",NA,115129,"2015-11-21 20:51:43 -0700","2017-09-25 21:49:34 -0700","research","CC-BY-NC",NA,"false"

"Pieris rapae","2015-04-09 14:15:00 -0700","This is a Cabbage White butterfly (Pieris rapae) that I photographed while out on my bi-weekly <a href=""http://research.nhm.org/bioscan/bioscanbuzz/?p=652"" rel=""nofollow"">ButterflySCAN</a> outing. ButterflySCAN is a <a href=""http://www.nhm.org/site/activities-programs/citizen-science"" rel=""nofollow"">Citizen Science</a> project of the <a href=""https://www.nhm.org"" rel=""nofollow"">Los Angeles County Natural History Museum</a>.

For the ButterflySCAN project, I have been assigned a location to explore every two weeks. My site is called Solano Canyon and is located northwest of downtown Los Angeles. (I enjoy this activity so much that sometimes I go every week, or every week-and-a-half, rather than waiting the full two weeks.) During my outing I walk through the neighborhood looking for, and counting, the various butterflies that I encounter. I also try to get photos of the butterflies that I see. (This photo is one that I took recently.)

I also record my butterfly observations on the <a href=""http://e-butterfly.org/contents/?portal=ebutterfly"" rel=""nofollow"">e-Butterfly.org</a> website.","Solano Canyon, Los Angeles, California",34.077941,-118.234214,"Cabbage White, Pieris Rapae, butterfly, e-Butterfly.org, ButterflySCAN, Los Angeles County Natural History Museum, NHMLA, nhm.org","Cabbage White","http://www.inaturalist.org/observations/1383841","https://static.inaturalist.org/photos/1709971/medium.jpg?1444333609","mgronwold",1383841,"Cabbage white butterfly","Insecta",55626,"true",2,0,"2015-04-09 14:15","2015-04-09","2015-04-09 14:15:00 -0700","Pacific Time (US & Canada)",2,"","","false","","",NA,48084,"2015-04-11 00:05:03 -0700","2015-09-09 14:33:06 -0700","research","CC-BY-NC-ND",NA,"false"

"Pieris rapae","2012-03-12 12:30:00 +1300","Butterfly comment: As soon as the sun came out from behind the clouds and the temperature started to warm, the Cabbage White became evident in this area. They were seen doing a variety of different activities, however many were seen flying between plantlife and resting for only small amounts of time. They seemed very \energetic\ and there was very little resting for long periods of time to be seen.

For the plant identifications in the photos, see the <a href=""http://naturewatch.org.nz/observations/954131"">rosemary plant observation</a>, <a href=""http://naturewatch.org.nz/observations/954426"">the blue flowers</a>, and the <a href=""http://naturewatch.org.nz/observations/954427"">pink flowers</a>.

Site notes: Conditions were ideal for butterfly activity as it was warm and sunny. There were some clouds visible at the begginning of the 20 minute interval but this burnt off quickly and the number of butterflies in the area became evident. The flowers were all very bright nd colourful which encouraged many butterflies to the area.. "Pieris rapae","2014-03-23 15:51:00 -0700","This butterfly was a creamy white with three or four black spots going down the wing I could see from where I was standing. It was about 2 inches in length, and it was constantly in motion as I tried to take a picture of it. 

I have seen this kind of butterfly before in this same place in the past, and it tended to keep gravitating towards the grapefruit tree and a growing orange tree. For these reasons, I think that it helps with pollination and feeds off the nectar of these plants.

It is non native to this country, having spread here from Canada after having been introduced there from Europe. "Pieris rapae","2011-07-07 12:23:22 -0700","The ubiquitous cabbage white butterfly is as common in coastal southern California as it is in New Zealand. It's a successful creature.

In this garden the many butterflies were laying eggs on, and larvae were feeding on, garden nasturtiums (<em>Tropaeolum majus</em>). I've read that nasturtiums independently evolved the same defensive chemistry as <em>Brassica</em>, the usual hosts of this butterfly, making them a suitable host plant despite not being closely related to <em>Brassica</em>.","Seal Beach, California, United States",33.776581,-118.094658,"garden","Cabbage White","http://www.inaturalist.org/observations/413419","https://static.inaturalist.org/photos/520406/medium.jpg?1444272565","jon_sullivan",413419,"Cabbage White","Insecta",55626,"false",1,0,"2011-07-07 12:23:22","2011-07-07","2011-07-07 12:23:22 -0700","Pacific Time (US & Canada)",NA,"","","false",NA,"",NA,1115,"2013-09-30 21:27:30 -0700","2015-05-13 17:15:50 -0700","research","CC-BY",NA,"false"

"Pieris rapae","2012-05-19 10:59:50 -0700","Also known as small white. Easy to distinguish the difference between - males only have one spot on the outer corner of their wings, females have two dark spots mid wing.  They are not native to the PNW and are originally from Europe, they compete with our native white - to their detriment.  An interesting, easily observed behavior is their spiral flight - usually done by a female to show a male that she is not interested in mating.  Mark-recapture can be done in one's own neighborhood by marking their wings with nail polish.","4005 Latona Ave NE, Seattle, Washington, US",47.655898,-122.324242,"","Cabbage White","http://www.inaturalist.org/observations/80554","https://static.inaturalist.org/photos/118670/medium.jpg","jmarcello1",80554,"Cabbage White","Insecta",55626,"false",1,0,"Sat May 19 2012 10:59:50 GMT-0700 (PDT)","2012-05-19","2012-05-19 10:59:50 -0700","Pacific Time (US & Canada)",10,"","","false","","",NA,5606,"2012-05-19 14:08:26 -0700","2015-05-13 17:51:12 -0700","research","CC-BY",NA,"false"

"Pieris rapae","2005-06-07 14:04:00 -0400","I saw this butterfly flying, but it looked a little funny.  Turned out it was 2 butterflies!  There was only one flapping its wings; the other was just along for the ride.  Maybe they had different ideas about whether they wanted to go somewhere or not. :-)  Or maybe going somewhere only works if 1 does the flying for both!  Got this shot when they set down.  Wingspan ~ 5 cm.

This is the Cabbage White, one of only 2 nonnative butterfly species in New Jersey.  Unfortunately, it seems to be the most common butterfly, at least around human habitation.
